snippet.textDisplay:
A foreword to all the vaccine skeptics in the comments section rooting for Mr Novak: if the current vaccines undoubtedly don't prevent future transmissions of the virus, becoming naturally immune from a previous infection doesn't make you infectiousless later on either.

So with that out of the way, yes, the Australian government is very much in the wrong for all the bureaucratic shenanigans it unleashed on Djokovic, but the latter is no Saint either -- far from it, as outside of his extremely-questionable act of attending a close-quarters public event a literal day after being knowingly tested positive, his high social position as a result of his high standing in sports has willingly or not been promoting an arguably self-destructive mentality towards this pandemic; not everyone is as well-fit as him, and if everyone was as vaccine-hesitant, so many more would still be heavily hospitalized and many of those would've died from the very possible and very real complications of this virus.

There is quite simply no Right Side to this threesome charade between governmental overreach, ill-founded paranoia and big pharma cash-in -- only the simple and undeniable fact that most Covid vaccines have saved more lives by preventing worst case scenarios on the individual level than they actually have killed through real but overdramatized side effects, and by an uncontestably wide margin at that.

So while, yes, Mr Novak Djokovic doesn't _personally_ need the vaccine himself, he has since become far too big of a public icon to do otherwise -- especially if he still wants to seem honest to the world in thanking _his_ fans for _their_ support.
